{{hatnote|For the German archaeologist, see [[Ernst Curtius]]}} '''Ernst Robert Curtius''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|ʊər|t|s|i|ʊ|s}}; April 14, 1886 &ndash; April 19, 1956) was a [[Germany|German]] literary scholar, [[philologist]], and Romance language literary critic, best known for his 1948 study ''Europäische Literatur und Lateinisches Mittelalter'', translated in English as ''European Literature and the Latin Middle Ages''.
==Biography== Curtius was [[Alsace|Alsatian]], born in [[Thann, Haut-Rhin|Thann]], into a north German family; [[Ernst Curtius]], his grandfather, and [[Georg Curtius]], his great-uncle, were both notable scholars. His family moved to [[Strasbourg]] after his father [[Friedrich Curtius]] was appointed president of the Lutheran [[Protestant Church of Augsburg Confession of Alsace and Lorraine]], and Curtius received his Abitur from the Strasbourg Protestant gymnasium.<ref name="ostheeren">{{cite book|last=Ostheeren|first=Klaus|editor=[[Helen Damico]]|title=Medieval Scholarship: Literature and Philology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IwWuEy-E268C&pg=PA373|accessdate=23 April 2012|year=1998|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-8153-2890-2|pages=365–80|chapter=Ernst Robert Curtius (1886-1956)}}</ref> He traveled in Europe afterward, and was fluent in French and English. [[Albert Schweitzer]], who boarded with the family between 1906 and 1912, is credited with introducing Curtius to modern French literature; of great influence also was the Romance philologist [[Gustav Gröber]].<ref name="ostheeren"/> He studied philology and philosophy in [[University of Strasbourg|Strasbourg]] (doctorate, 1910), [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Berlin]], and [[University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]]; he wrote his ''Habilitationsschrift'' for Gröber in [[University of Bonn|Bonn]], 1913, and began teaching there in 1914. [[World War I]] interrupted his scholarly work: Curtius served in France and Poland and was wounded in 1915; his injuries were severe enough for him to be discharged in 1916; he returned to Bonn to resume teaching.<ref name="ostheeren"/>
==Work== Much of Curtius's work was done while the Nazis were in power, and his interest in humanist studies is usually seen as a response to the totalitarianism of his times. Curtius saw European literature as part of a continuous tradition that began with the Greek and Latin authors and continued throughout the Middle Ages; he did not acknowledge a break between those traditions, a division that would separate historical periods from each other and support a set of national literatures without connections to each other. Greatly interested in French literature, early in his career he promoted the study of that literature in a period in Germany when it was considered the enemy's literature, a "humanist and heroic" stance that earned him the criticism of the nationalist intelligentsia in Germany.<ref name="calin"/>
He is best known for his 1948 work ''Europäische Literatur und Lateinisches Mittelalter''.<ref>Translated in English as ''[[European Literature and the Latin Middle Ages]]'', by Willard R. Trask. New York: Harper Row, 1953. {{ISBN|0-691-01899-5}}</ref> It was a major study of the [[Medieval Latin]] literature and its effect on subsequent writing in modern [[European languages]], and argued that, first, the standard "Classic-Medieval-Renaissance-Modern" division of literature was counterproductive given the continuity between those literatures, and second, that "much of Renaissance and later European literature cannot be fully understood without a knowledge of that literature's relation to Medieval Latin rhetoric in the use of commonplaces, metaphors, turns of phrase, or, to employ the term Curtius prefers, ''topoi''".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lind|first=L.R.|year=1951|title=Rev. of Curtius, ''Europäische Literatur und lateinisches Mittelalter''|journal=[[The Classical Weekly]]|volume=44|issue=14|pages=220–21|jstor=4342972}}</ref> The book was largely responsible for introducing the "literary topos" concept as a scholarly and critical discussion of literary [[Literary topos|commonplaces]].<ref name="calin">{{cite book|last=Calin|first=William|editor=Leslie J. Workman|others=Kathleen Verduin, David D. Metzger|title=Medievalism and the Academy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r_XODDph6c0C&pg=PA221|accessdate=23 April 2012|year=1999|publisher=D. S. Brewer|isbn=978-0-85991-532-8|pages=218–27|chapter=Ernst Robert Curtius: The Achievement of a Humanist}}</ref><ref name="Huhtamo2011">{{cite book|last=Huhtamo|first=Erkki|editor=Erkki Huhtamo|title=Media Archaeology: Approaches, Applications, and Implications|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aSlQ8z1uslwC&pg=PT56|accessdate=23 April 2012|date=2011-05-17|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-94851-8|page=56|chapter=Dismantling the Fairy Engine: Media Archeology as Topos Study}}</ref>
==Bibliography== * ''Die literarischen Wegbereiter des neuen Frankreich'' (1919) * ''Die Französische Kultur'' (1931, translation as ''The Civilization of France: An Introduction'' (1932) * ''Deutscher Geist in Gefahr'' (1932) * "Zur Literarästhetik des Mittelalters," ''Zeitschrift für romanische Philologie'' 58 (1938), 1–50, 129–232, and 433–79 * ''Europäische Literatur und lateinisches Mittelalter'' (1948) * ''Französischer Geist im 20. Jahrhundert'' (1952)
