'''Nancy Currier Dorian''' is an American [[linguistics|linguist]] who has carried out research into the decline of the [[East Sutherland Gaelic|East Sutherland dialect]] of [[Scottish Gaelic]] for over 40 years, particularly in the villages of [[Brora]], [[Golspie]] and [[Embo]]. Due to their isolation from other Gaelic-speaking communities, these East Sutherland villages presented a good opportunity to study [[language death]]. Dorian's study is possibly the longest such study in the field. She is considered "a prime authority" on language death.{{sfn|Drechsel|1990|p=554}} ''Language Death: The Life Cycle of a Scottish Gaelic Dialect'', her study into the decline of Gaelic in East Sutherland, is considered "the first major monograph"{{sfn|Dressler|1982|p=432}} on language death. According to linguist Joan Argenter, Dorian's name "is well known to scholars working in" several areas of linguistics.{{sfn|Argenter|2015|p=331}}

==Life==
